\[
\text{By Vieta’s formulas, the sum of the zeros is } -\frac{b_{11}}{b_{12}} = -\frac{-21}{5} = \frac{21}{5}, \text{ which is not an integer. Since the zeros are negative integers, their sum must be an integer. Hence, no such polynomial exists.}
\]

\[
\textbf{Corrected Step:} \text{ By the Whitney Extension Theorem, if } g\colon C\to\mathbb{R} \text{ is smooth in the Whitney sense on any closed set } C\subset \mathbb{R}^n, \text{ then there exists } f\in C^\infty(\mathbb{R}^n) \text{ such that } f|_C=g, \text{ even when } C \text{ is not compact. Therefore, the answer is } \textbf{Yes.}
\]

